> # RED FLAG EXAMPLES
> 
> # Example 1: red flag catches a nonlinearity
> # True model is quadratic: y = x^2
> set.seed(123)
> x <- runif(200, -3, 3)
> y <- x^2 + rnorm(200, sd = 2)
> 
> # lm2() shows red flag due to misspecification
> lm2(y ~ x)
Call: lm2(formula = y ~ x)

            estimate SE.robust SE.classical t.value p.value std.estimate   mean
intercept   2.698**    0.228      0.226     11.81    <.0001       --        -- 
x           0.151      0.175      0.138     0.862     .3895    0.078     0.038 
            missing red.flag
intercept     --        --  
x             0         !   

N = 200  | missing = 0  | df = 198  | R² = 0.006  | SE type: HC3 

Notes:
  - ** p<.01 (based on SE.robust)
  - std.estimate is the standardized coefficient: beta = b * sd(x) / sd(y)
  - mean: for numeric variables, mean of x; for factors, % of observations
  - missing: number of observations excluded due to missing values
  - red.flag:
     !: robust & classical SE differ by more than 25%
     - Suggestion 1: to evaluate possible extreme skew or outliers:
       plot_density() or plot_freq() for y and for x
     - Suggestion 2: to evaluate possible nonlinearity, do plot_gam(y ~ x)
  - To avoid these notes, lm2(..., notes=FALSE)
> 
> # Follow up with scatter.gam() to diagnose it
> scatter.gam(x, y)
> 
> # Example 2: red flag catches an outlier in y
> # True model is y = x, but one observation has a very large y value
> set.seed(123)
> x <- sort(rnorm(200))
> y <- round(x + rnorm(200, sd = 2), 1)
> y[200] <- 100  # Outlier
> 
> # lm2() flags x
> lm2(y ~ x)
Call: lm2(formula = y ~ x)

            estimate SE.robust SE.classical t.value p.value std.estimate
intercept   0.585      0.535      0.493     1.092     .2760       --    
x           2.628      1.804      0.524     1.457     .1468    0.336    
              mean  missing red.flag
intercept       --    --        --  
x           -.0086    0         !!! 

N = 200  | missing = 0  | df = 198  | R² = 0.113  | SE type: HC3 

Notes:
  - All estimates are p>.1 (based on SE.robust)
  - std.estimate is the standardized coefficient: beta = b * sd(x) / sd(y)
  - mean: for numeric variables, mean of x; for factors, % of observations
  - missing: number of observations excluded due to missing values
  - red.flag:
     !!!: robust & classical SE differ by more than 100%
     - Suggestion 1: to evaluate possible extreme skew or outliers:
       plot_density() or plot_freq() for y and for x
     - Suggestion 2: to evaluate possible nonlinearity, do plot_gam(y ~ x)
  - To avoid these notes, lm2(..., notes=FALSE)
> 
> # Look at distribution of y to spot the outlier
> plot_freq(y)

plot_freq() says: because there are more than 30 unique values, frequency was printed only for the mode. Set  `value.labels` to modify this behavior> 
